description: From Middle English oken (also eken), from Old English ācen, ǣcen (“of oak”), from Proto-Germanic *aikīnaz, equivalent to oak +‎ -en (adjectival suffix). Cognate with Dutch eiken (“oaken”), German eichen (“oaken”), Icelandic eikinn (“oaken”).

entries.meaning: Made from the wood of the oak tree.  Also in metaphorical uses, suggesting robustness.
